@eschmidscs The strategy would be to run many times and check the average and see that observed stall probability it is within the theoretical value with some arbitrary selected margin. Since the random seed is always the same the test will not sporadically fail and be robust. 

The verification components typically use OSVVM inside with a fixed random seed. To my knowledge there is no way to create a true random value in VHDL that will differ between runs unless a random seed is injected from outside the simulation via generic. 

Still modifying something about the test sequence might change which value in the random sequence are used and cause the test to fail unintentionally, the likelihood that the average will be outside the margin when running many iterations can still be kept very small.

